recordings.loc: Chehalis, Lewis County, Washington
recordings.rmk: "Squeak song", as I have deemed it. Heard on multiple occasions by different individuals in this region. Long-winded, but often quiet, high-pitched squeaking that turns into a standard song at times, begging calls at times, scolding calls at times... It's weird. It always sounds more like a baby bird to me until it lapses into song all of a sudden. Slightest bit of amplification used, since the squeak song is decently quiet even at close recording range (<5m). It was doing this nearly continuously (with several short [~2 second] pauses, such as what I used for the beginning and end of this recording) for about 15-20 minutes while foraging in smallish (~12m) deciduous trees. Immediately after the end of this recording, it started its "typical" full-bodied song. Weather: calm (but with a very slight breeze), clear, warm (~70 degrees F). Singing from mid- to lower branches of a birch tree, about 5-6m above the ground.

recordings.loc: Jardin Botanico, Quito
recordings.rmk:
First record for Ecuador! The bird was first found near the first pond. I heard it calling and didn't recognize the sound. When I saw it, I saw that it was a vireo but it looked very dull. A Red-eyed had been in this bush a couple of weeks before but I could soon see that it wasn't that and it had no yellow anywhere and ho strong head pattern, just an obvious supercilium. It also sub-sang a bit in-between the calls. I went around and played the call back and it immediately came in and hoped about over-head allowing for pictures. It responded with a soft 'tchep' call . This repeated several times between 7:45 and 8:20 when the bird was seen flying out (south) of the BG and was not seen by me later. All plain grey-brown above and off-white below with random buffier patches on the side of the breast. Faint eye-line and whitish supercilium, otherwise lacked obvious fieldmarks, except for the three different call-types. On this cut are the soft 'tchep' notes and towards the end two calls.
